Yes — and that’s actually the better and cleaner approach 👍

Instead of Jenkins (public EC2) doing everything via SSH, you can:

👉 Configure the Private EC2 as a Jenkins Agent
👉 Run backend build + deploy directly on the agent

This is how real-world CI/CD is usually done.

🧱 Updated 3-Tier with Jenkins Agent
Jenkins (Public EC2 - Controller)
 └── Builds Frontend (runs here)

Private EC2 (Agent)
 └── Builds Backend
 └── Runs Backend container
 └── Runs Database container
✅ Why This is Better
❌ Your current method (SSH)
Manual SSH
Image transfer (scp)
Hard to scale
✅ Agent-based method
Native Jenkins execution
No SSH hacks in pipeline
Cleaner & scalable
⚙️ Step 1: Configure Private EC2 as Agent

You already did:

ssh-keygen on Jenkins
ssh-copy-id to private EC2

Now in Jenkins:

Manage Jenkins → Nodes → New Node

Name: backend-agent
Type: Permanent Agent
Configure:
Remote root dir: /home/ec2-user
Launch method: Launch via SSH
Host: <PRIVATE_IP>
Credentials: SSH private key
⚙️ Step 2: Install Docker on Agent (Important)

SSH into private EC2:

sudo yum install docker -y
sudo systemctl start docker
sudo systemctl enable docker
sudo usermod -aG docker ec2-user
🔥 Step 3: Clean Jenkins Pipeline (Agent-Based)

Now your pipeline becomes much simpler 👇

pipeline {
    agent none

    stages {

        stage('Frontend Build & Deploy') {
            agent any
            steps {
                git 'https://github.com/your-repo.git'

                sh 'docker build -t frontend ./frontend'

                sh '''
                docker rm -f frontend || true
                docker run -d -p 80:80 --name frontend frontend
                '''
            }
        }

        stage('Backend + DB Deploy (Private EC2)') {
            agent { label 'backend-agent' }

            steps {
                git 'https://github.com/your-repo.git'

                sh 'docker build -t backend ./backend'

                sh '''
                docker rm -f backend mysql || true
                docker network rm app-net || true

                docker network create app-net

                docker run -d \
                  --name mysql \
                  --network app-net \
                  -e MYSQL_ROOT_PASSWORD=root \
                  -e MYSQL_DATABASE=mydb \
                  mysql:8

                docker run -d \
                  --name backend \
                  --network app-net \
                  -p 5000:5000 \
                  -e DB_HOST=mysql \
                  backend
                '''
            }
        }
    }
}
🔑 Key Difference
Before	Now
SSH into private EC2	Jenkins agent runs there
SCP images	Build happens there
Complex	Clean
⚠️ One Important Fix

Your security group must allow:

Jenkins → Private EC2 (port 22) ✅
Public EC2 → Private EC2 (port 5000) (for frontend API calls)
🚀 Even Better (Next Step)

Instead of building twice:

Build once → push to:
Amazon ECR
Agent pulls image → deploy
🧠 Real Industry Pattern

This is exactly how companies do:

Jenkins Controller → orchestration
Agents → workload execution
Private infra → secure deployments
✅ Final Answer

✔️ Yes, you should configure private EC2 as Jenkins agent
✔️ Yes, you can build + deploy backend there directly
✔️ This is better than SSH-based deployment

If you want next level:

✅ Multi-agent setup (dev / staging / prod)
✅ Auto-scaling Jenkins agents
✅ ECR-based pipeline (no rebuild duplication)
✅ Full production-grade CI/CD architecture